chatgpt_double_star.new_statement: Abortion laws should be built around a shared commitment to protect life and health in the real world: safeguard a pregnant person’s safety and agency while acknowledging that many people believe developing fetal life deserves increasing moral and legal consideration as pregnancy advances. A consensus approach keeps early care accessible and private, ties any later-pregnancy regulations to clear medical criteria and viability, and guarantees prompt exceptions for life endangerment, serious health impairment, fatal fetal conditions, and pregnancies from rape or incest—without criminal penalties that deter emergency treatment. Lasting common ground also requires reducing unwanted pregnancies and hardship through evidence-based education, affordable contraception, robust prenatal/postpartum care, and practical support for parenting and adoption.

chatgpt_double_star_rankings.new_statement: Abortion laws should aim to reduce preventable harm and protect human dignity by treating abortion primarily as a healthcare matter grounded in medical evidence, privacy, and the patient–clinician relationship. A workable framework preserves timely access early in pregnancy and sets clear, clinically defined rules for later pregnancy, with explicit exceptions for life-threatening emergencies, serious health risks, nonviable pregnancies, and cases involving violence—written so doctors can act without fear and patients are not criminalized. Whatever limits exist, policy should also invest in prevention and real support—accurate education, affordable contraception, prenatal and postpartum care, and practical help for parenting and adoption—so fewer families face crisis decisions at all.
